
[1]diffuse

   DIFFUSE, v.t. diffuze. [L., to pour, to spread.]

   1. To pour out and spread, as a fluid; to cause to flow and spread.

   The river rose and diffused its waters over the adjacent plain.

   2. To spread; to send out or extend in all directions; to disperse.
   Flowers diffuse their odors. The fame of Washington is diffused over
   Europe. The knowledge of the true God will be diffused over the earth.

                                 DIFFUSE, a.

   1. Widely spread; dispersed.

   2. Copious; prolix; using many words; giving full descriptions; as,
   Livy is a diffuse writer.

   3. Copious; verbose; containing full or particular accounts; concise;
   as a diffuse style.
